---------------------------------------
COVID-19 DEATH TREND DATA VISUALISATION
---------------------------------------

The goal of this project is to provide a bespoke visualisation of COVID-19 death data 
for the use of junior government officials looking to make decisions based on the current 
death trends.

The project has been produced in Python 3.9.

REQUIREMENTS 
---------------------------------------

* calendar -- pip install calendar
* pandas -- pip install pandas
* pandas.io.json -- pip install pandas.io.json
* plotly -- pip install plotly
* plotly.express -- pip install plotly-express
* plotly.graph_objects 
* dash -- pip install dash
* json -- pip install json
* geojson_rewind -- pip install geojson-rewind

OTHER REFERENCES 
---------------------------------------

EXTERNAL STYLESHEET: https://codepen.io/chriddyp/pen/bWLwgP.css
Parmer, C., 2022. Dash Styleguide. [online] codepen.io. 
	Available at: <https://codepen.io/chriddyp/pen/bWLwgP> [Accessed 5 January 2022].
 

NHSE CSV SOURCE: nhse_total_deaths_by_region.csv
Greater London Authority. (2021) nhse_total_deaths_by_region.csv - data.gov.uk. [online] Data.gov.uk. 
	Available at: https://data.gov.uk/dataset/43b2334a-6970-4e71-a27a-630dc4901e04/coronavirus-covid-19-deaths	[Accessed 3 December 2021].
* The version of this csv used in the programme has been modified to only include data from August, September and October 2021, 
	however the code has been structured to function with 12 months of data.
	
GEOJSON SOURCE: NHS_England_Regions_(April_2020)_Boundaries_EN_BGC.geojson
Office for National Statistics (2020) Data.gov.uk: NHS England Regions (April 2020) Boundaries EN BGC - data.gov.uk. 
	Available from: https://data.gov.uk/dataset/66a7bb97-3da6-4e19-975b-1f0784909cd5/nhs-england-regions-april-2020-boundaries-en-bgc [Accessed 28 December 2021].

RUNNING THE PROGRAMME
---------------------------------------

Open the Powershell Window within the programme folder
	(Ctrl + Right-click and choose "Open Powershell Window here")

Type: python cetm25_stacy_oswald.py

Then press enter. This will initialise the dash window.

Open your browser and navigate to http://127.0.0.1:8050/

This will then load the data dashboard webpage ready for use